CSS.content:
In SCSS (and CSS), HTML attributes are targeted with square brackets `[]`, not parentheses.

**Targeting disabled attribute:**
```scss
button {
  &[disabled] {
    opacity: 0.5;
    cursor: not-allowed;
  }
}
```

**Targeting data attributes:**
```scss
.card {
  &[data-variant="primary"] {
    background: blue;
  }
}
```

**Breakdown:**
- `&` acts as the parent selector reference
- `[disabled]` targets elements with the disabled attribute

The `:has()` pseudo-class allows styling based on whether an element contains specific children or states.

**1. Parent Selection:**
```css
/* Style divs that contain images */
div:has(img) {
  padding: 1rem;
}
```

**2. Conditional Styling:**
```css
/* Style form fields with error messages */
.form-field:has(.error-message) {
  border-color: red;
}
```

**3. State-Based Styling:**
```css
/* Style card when button is hovered */
.card:has(button:hover) {
  box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
}
```

**Real-world Example:**
```css
/* Adjust position when navbar is visible */
body:has(.is-scroll-up) .faqs-categories {
  top: 6.5rem;
}
```

`:has()` is a forward-looking selector that significantly expands CSS capabilities, reducing the need for JavaScript.

The `&` symbol in SCSS can target the parent element when it's inside a specific context.

**Example:**
```scss
.hero__title {
  // Base styles for desktop
  font-size: 3rem;

  .hero__content--mobile & {
    // Styles when inside mobile context
    font-size: 2rem;
  }
}
```

**Compiles to:**
```css
.hero__content--mobile .hero__title {
  font-size: 2rem;
}
```

**Meaning:** "Apply these styles to `.hero__title` only when it's inside `.hero__content--mobile`"

The `&` lets you write nested styles that target the current element in a specific context.

Setting all four positional parameters to 0 makes an absolutely positioned element fill its parent.

**Example:**
```css
.hero__content--mobile {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
}
```

This makes the element take up the entire parent container (which must have `position: relative` or another positioning context).

Use this combination for flexible, scalable elements:

```css
.element {
  aspect-ratio: 16/9;
  min-height: 300px;
  height: auto;
}
```

**How it works:**
- `height: auto` calculates: `height = width ÷ aspect-ratio`
- As viewport width changes, height recalculates automatically
- `min-height` prevents element from becoming too small

This creates responsive elements that maintain aspect ratio while scaling with the viewport.

The `dvh` (dynamic viewport height) unit adjusts to visible viewport changes.

**How it works:**
- `1dvh` = 1% of currently visible viewport height
- Automatically adjusts when browser UI appears/disappears
- Switches between large viewport (lvh) and small viewport (svh)

**Comparison:**
```css
/* Traditional - can cause issues on mobile */
.hero {
  height: 100vh;
}

/* Dynamic - always matches visible height */
.hero {
  height: 100dvh;
}
```

**Benefits:**
- Handles mobile browser address bars
- Accounts for on-screen keyboards
- Provides smooth, dynamic measurement

Unlike `vh`, `dvh` reflects actual visible height at any moment.

`max-width` sets boundaries while letting content flow naturally.

**Bad Approach - Fighting the browser:**
```css
.element {
  width: 100%;

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    width: 90%;
  }

  @media (max-width: 480px) {
    width: 95%;
  }
}
```

**Good Approach - Set boundaries:**
```css
.element {
  max-width: 600px;  /* Never wider than this */
  width: 100%;       /* Use available space up to limit */
}
```

**Benefits:**
- Set upper boundaries where things break down
- Let elements shrink naturally below that point
- Saves writing multiple media queries
- Children inherit the constraint

Enable scrolling for fixed/floating elements that overflow on landscape mobile viewports.

**Solution:**
```css
@media (max-height: 451px) and (orientation: landscape) {
  .nav-menu {
    height: 300px;
    overflow-y: scroll;
    -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch; /* iOS smooth scrolling */
  }
}
```

**Why this works:**
- Defined height is essential (without it, no scrolling)
- Enables scrolling when content exceeds viewport
- Avoids complex media query workarounds
- Provides smooth scrolling on iOS

Two levels of styling in Vue/component-based apps:

**Component Level:**
```vue
<!-- ProjectCard.vue -->
<style scoped>
.project-card {
  padding: var(--spacing-lg);
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .project-card {
    padding: var(--spacing-md);
  }
}
</style>
```

**Container Level:**
```vue
<!-- ProjectsSection.vue -->
<style scoped>
.projects-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr));
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .projects-grid {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
}
</style>
```

**Best Strategy:**
- Components handle internal responsive behavior
- Containers handle overall page structure changes
- Global styles maintain consistency via CSS variables

`width: auto` is ideal for responsive images when controlling size with height.

**Example:**
```css
img {
  height: 300px;
  width: auto;
  max-width: 100%;
}
```

**Benefits:**
- Maintains aspect ratio automatically
- Prevents distortion
- Respects `max-width` constraint
- Better performance (no conflicting calculations)

Width adjusts automatically to match the height constraint while preserving the image's natural proportions.
